DESIGN DECISIONS (O9.1, this round)
D1. Backup step order: point 8 runs AFTER heartbeat (point 7), last before
    the finale — the workdir is complete at that moment, so the initial
    push captures the whole installed state.
D2. Repo name: fixed "qroky-backup" (private). Restore command printed at
    success and documented in READMEs: `gh repo clone qroky-backup` (one
    command; gh resolves the user's own account — no need to know a URL).
    README adds: after restore, run install.sh once in the clone to
    reattach the pinned rulebook (submodule).
D3. Secrets exclusion: a .gitignore is written into the user workdir at
    opt-in time (check->do: only appended if the marker block is absent),
    excluding .qroky/telegram.token, *.token, .env*, *.pem, *.key,
    *secret*, *credential*, and install.log (logs carry the masked-token
    audit line; excluding them entirely is stricter than needed but
    cheaper to reason about). The harness proves the exclusion on the
    PUSHED tree, not the working tree: the gh stub's `repo create --push`
    performs a real `git push` into a local bare repo, and the scenario
    greps that bare repo's full history for the raw token AND checks
    `ls-tree` for the token filename — both must be empty while the tree
    itself must be non-empty (install-state.json present) so the check
    cannot pass vacuously.
D4. gh commit identity: a fresh non-technical machine often has no
    git user.email; the backup commit falls back to -c user.name/email
    ("Qroky backup <qroky-backup@local>") only when the user has none —
    never overriding an existing identity.
D5. Failure shape per INPUT: gh missing -> plain-language install hint +
    continue without backup + enable-later command (no ladder — installing
    software has no automatic remedy, same reasoning as the Claude Code
    step, ATOM-101 Decision 6). gh auth failure -> human-language message,
    continue without backup. Mechanical part (add/commit/create/push) runs
    through run_with_ladder (2 auto-retries — network push is a real
    transient-failure candidate); final failure = concrete human action +
    install continues, exit 0.
D6. New flag `bash install.sh --enable-backup` (mirrors --enable-heartbeat)
    = the documented enable-later path for opt-outs; reuses the same flow
    functions, resolve_and_load_state first.
D7. Transcript destination switched: dry-run.sh's ATOM_WORKSPACE now
    points at 102-kit-amendment/workspace/ per INPUT §4 — the committed
    101 transcripts remain untouched as round-2 evidence.

